{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "We address the question of understanding the production of J/\u03c8 particles regarding the global underlying event in proton-proton collisions. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "To do so, we propose to look at a new observable: the J/\u03c8 production as a function of the charged particles multiplicity of the event. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "We demonstrate the interest for an experimental measurement by varying the model of multiple interactions in the PYTHIA generator.",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Understanding the production of the J/\u03c8 particle in proton-proton collisions is a complex issue [1,2]. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 96,
                    "end": 99,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 99,
                    "end": 101,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It becomes even more complex when one considers the production of a J/\u03c8 in a complete event containing interplaying soft and hard components produced simultaneously. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In this first section, we provide motivations for studying quarkonia production regarding the complete proton+proton event. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "We emphasize that proton-proton collisions are not trivial, especially in the regime of high multiplicity events.",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Very few observables have been studied as a function of the charged particles multiplicity. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The CDF collaboration conducted such a study for the mean transverse momentum p T , as illustrated on Fig 1. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 102,
                    "end": 108,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig 1."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "An important raise of p T is seen as a function of multiplicity. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "This can result from several elementary multiple interactions occurring in parallel in growing multiplicity events. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In these events, one can also expects non trivial phenomenon, such as collective effects, as mentioned later. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus, there is no theoretical clear picture for the explanation of p T versus multiplicity, but multiple interactions clearly play an important role. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Another feature that helps to understand the importance of multiple interactions, is the fact that, for protonproton collisions, the jet cross section computed in the framework of perturbative Quantum Chromodynamics (pQCD), becomes larger than the total cross section:",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Email addresses: sarah.porteboeuf@clermont.in2p3.fr (S. Porteboeuf), raphael@in2p3.fr (R. Granier de Cassagnac) there is thus more than one elementary collision in high multiplicity events [3].  ",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 189,
                    "end": 192,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 5,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Email",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "On Fig. 1, authors compared this observable with the event generator PYTHIA [5]. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 3,
                    "end": 9,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 76,
                    "end": 79,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 69,
                    "end": 75,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "These event generator is based on pQCD and assume the factorization scheme. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "At the time the CDF data, Run I, was released, none of the models were able to describe the data [6]. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 97,
                    "end": 100,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "After improving its treatment of multiple interactions, PYTHIA finally describes better these data with the tune\u00c2 (p \u22a5 = 1.5) [4]. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 126,
                    "end": 129,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[4]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 56,
                    "end": 62,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A good understanding of high multiplicity phenomena is thus important to completely describe events with hard and soft components, and possible interactions between the two. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "It is to be noted that collective effects in proton-proton collisions can also contribute to explaining this observable, as for instance accounted in the EPOS event generator [7].",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 175,
                    "end": 178,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The only other multiplicity dependence study that we are aware of is from one of the first UA1 paper where the authors studied the transverse energy E T as a function of multiplicity [8]. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 183,
                    "end": 186,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Besides these CDF and UA1 observations, and a recent CMS result that will be mentioned hereafter, high multiplicity phenomena in protonproton collisions are not studied. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "On the opposite, in heavy-ions collisions, studying observables as a function of the (very high) multiplicity is a key concept and a very common tool to study the Quark Gluon Plasma (QGP).",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "In standard proton-proton collisions, J/\u03c8 are produced through hard processes. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Hard processes can be understood in the framework of pQCD, where in the limit of high momentum transfer Q 2 , a hard component (2 \u2192 2 or 2 \u2192 1 processes) can be factorized out from the soft component, as predicted by the factorization theorem [9,10]. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 243,
                    "end": 246,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[9,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 246,
                    "end": 249,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "J/\u03c8 are very particular among the hard probes, because they first imply the production of a massive charm quark-antiquark pair, followed by its binding into a charmonia (cc) state. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Nowadays, the exact charmonia production scheme is not clear and is debated within the community (for reviews on this aspect, see [1,2]). ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 130,
                    "end": 133,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 133,
                    "end": 135,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Furthermore, no models describe the underlying event associated to a J/\u03c8 production, and one needs to be aware of this lack of description, when dealing with event generators. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "This problem was for instance raised in February 2010 during a workshop on quarkonia production at CERN [11]. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 104,
                    "end": 108,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[11]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "New observables are then needed to start understanding and constraining the interplay of soft and hard aspects of proton-proton collisions, the importance of multiple interactions in the production of hard processes and the possibility of new phenomena such as collective effects.",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The simple new observable we propose to look at is the J/\u03c8 yield versus the underlying event multiplicity. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The basic idea is to compare the multiplicity of events containing a J/\u03c8 to the multiplicity of Minimum Bias events. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The physics that we want to address here is the interplay between the hard (J/\u03c8) and the soft (underlying) components in a complete event, the influence of one over the other, in the case of quarkonia production such as the J/\u03c8. ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The question is: do the underlying event and the multiple interactions scheme matter in the production of hard processes, such as a J/\u03c8? ",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Though we limit ourselves to the case of J/\u03c8, we think the complete understanding of global events will only arise by studying as many quantities as possible, including various hard probes.",
            "section": "J/\u03c8 production in complete events",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 13,
                    "end": 19,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "To test the relevance of our new observable, we conducted a simple study at the event generator level. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "To do so, we needed an event generator that is able to produce simultaneously the J/\u03c8 and the corresponding underlying event. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "PYTHIA is one of the most developed event generator having the two functionalities. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 6,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Other event generators have more sophisticated description of the soft component (HERWIG [12], EPOS [13]), but none of them include the production of quarkonia. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 89,
                    "end": 93,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[12]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 100,
                    "end": 104,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[13]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Another possibility could be the CASCADE event generator [14], this could be explored.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 57,
                    "end": 61,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "[14]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "We generate two uncorrelated sets of PYTHIA events. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 37,
                    "end": 43,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w5"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In the first set, it is required to produce a J/\u03c8 in each event (ISUB=86), through the color singlet model used by default in PYTHIA [5]. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 133,
                    "end": 136,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 126,
                    "end": 132,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w6"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The second set is made of Minimum Bias (MB) events (MSEL=2). ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The multiplicity distribution is determined for the two sets and their ratio (J/\u03c8 \u00f7 MB) is computed, then normalized for the J/\u03c8 and MB cross sections, estimated by PYTHIA.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 165,
                    "end": 171,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w7"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It is to be noted here, that our J/\u03c8 are directly produced and do not come from B, \u03c7 c or \u03c8 \u2032 decays. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig. 2 shows this first result with a million generated events for each set, for proton-proton collisions at 10 TeV. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 6,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Here, Multiplicity stands for the number of charged particles with p T > 0.9 GeV/c and pseudorapidity lower than 2.4, corresponding to the acceptance of the CMS tracker. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "In all the PYTHIA tunes we considered, the J/\u03c8 production mechanism is the default one, meaning the Color Singlet model, but one should also looked at different implementations of the production mechanism for other birth processes (such as the Color Octet mechanism).",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 11,
                    "end": 17,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w8"
                },
                {
                    "start": 100,
                    "end": 105,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Color",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w9"
                },
                {
                    "start": 244,
                    "end": 249,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Color",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w10"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The four curves refer to different PYTHIA settings, mostly implying variation of the multiple interactions model.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 35,
                    "end": 41,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w11"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The green closed circle symbols account for basic PYTHIA, version 6.2, with all parameters set as default (MSTP(82)=1). ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 52,
                    "end": 58,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w12"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this simple model all interactions are supposed to be independent. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The number of parton-parton interactions in a protonproton collision follows a Poissonian law, with the mean number of interactionsn = \u03c3 hard /\u03c3 inelastic .",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Here, the hard process is the first one, the hardest one, the successive multiple interactions being then ordered by their hardness. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "There is no initial state radiations for interactions in the multiple scattering and no color connection between different ladders.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 For the red closed star symbols, the PYTHIA 6.2 tune D6 is used. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 39,
                    "end": 45,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w13"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This is the best tune for Tevatron data. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "With the PYTHIA parameter MSTP(82)=4, the model for multiple interactions is improved.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 9,
                    "end": 15,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w14"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Hadrons are considered to be extended objects.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The collision has an impact parameter which modifies the number of multiple interactions. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "When the protons overlap a lot, there is more chance to have multiple interactions than when there is less.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The blue closed triangle symbols is PYTHIA 6.4 all parameters by default, the model for multiple interactions is based on the model in PYTHIA 6.2, with a modification of the default values for different parameters (hard scale). ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 38,
                    "end": 44,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w15"
                },
                {
                    "start": 137,
                    "end": 143,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w16"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This is an intermediate version between PYTHIA 6.2 D6 and the new model.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 40,
                    "end": 46,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w17"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 For the purple closed square symbols, a new multiple interactions model was developed to be able to describe CDF data on p T (Fig. 1). ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 127,
                    "end": 135,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "(Fig. 1)"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this new model, based on the previous one for the determination of the number of interactions, initial state radiations are implemented with color reconnections between the strings produced by different interactions. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The first interaction is still the hardest one. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "With this new model, more particles are produced in event with a lot of multiple interactions, color re-connections are an important feature for the structure of the whole event.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "A detailed description of the physics implied in the different PYTHIA models for multiple interactions can be found in [5].",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 119,
                    "end": 122,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 63,
                    "end": 69,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w18"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The naive expectation is that, if the production of a J/\u03c8 has nothing to do with multiple interactions, we should observe a flat ratio on Fig. 2. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 138,
                    "end": 144,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It is clearly not the case, in all PYTHIA configurations. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 35,
                    "end": 41,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w19"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Furthermore, the results depends strongly on the PYTHIA model of multiple interactions assumed. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 49,
                    "end": 55,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w20"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Quite unexpected is the shape of the strongly decreasing curves we observe, especially in the most modern tunes. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "It is to be noted that the multiple interactions scheme in PYTHIA is still under study and the production of quarkonia is not well constrained, especially with the final state radiation, and the production mechanism.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 59,
                    "end": 65,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w21"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In any case, the physical meaning (in PYTHIA) of the different curves is hard to understand. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 38,
                    "end": 44,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w22"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A detailed study of all PYTHIA parameters would be necessary to identify what mechanism is responsible in PYTHIA for each kind of multiple interactions models, (initial sate interaction, final state interaction, pQCD scales, color re-connection...).",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 24,
                    "end": 30,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w23"
                },
                {
                    "start": 106,
                    "end": 112,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w24"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "More important is to study this observable in real data, for instance in the 7 TeV proton-proton data collected at LHC, and to compare the experimental behavior to the simulated ones. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "We do not expect PYTHIA to quantitatively predict such a new observable, for which the event generator was not built, but rather the experimental measurement to help tuning PYTHIA.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 17,
                    "end": 23,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w25"
                },
                {
                    "start": 173,
                    "end": 179,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w26"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "To interpret this future measurement, an important problem will be its normalization. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "For corresponding study in heavy-ions collisions, one compares to protonproton collisions, scaled by the number of equivalent proton-proton collisions. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Here we are looking only at proton-proton collisions: there is no such underlying elementary collisions concept. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The normalization is then not clear and can be debated.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "A possibility would be to compare with open charm. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Open charm are produced in standard 2 \u2192 2 hard processes. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "If J/\u03c8 has the same behavior as a standard hard processes from the multiplicity point of view, we should see a similar behavior. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "One can also think to look at different p T classes of the J/\u03c8 to look for eventual modification of the trend looking at hardest particles. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Finally, in a more general study, we would recommend to look at any observable, one could think of, as a function of multiplicity. ",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Taking hadrons or jets for example, one then could use another event generator than PYTHIA, with a different feature of multiple interactions, and collective phenomenon, and here, one could think of EPOS [13], that does not include, massive quarks and quarkonia production.",
            "section": "First simple PYTHIA study",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 204,
                    "end": 208,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[13]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 84,
                    "end": 90,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w27"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Conclusion",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "This first generator level study of J/\u03c8 production as a function of multiplicity shows that the production of J/\u03c8 in a complete event with the corresponding underlying event and multiple interactions scenario does not seem to be under control in the PYTHIA event generator. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 250,
                    "end": 256,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "PYTHIA",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w28"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Our recommendation is to perform this study with the new LHC data at 7 TeV in proton-proton collisions. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The ALICE, ATLAS, CMS and LHCb experiments have complementary acceptance. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "For instance, CMS can measure J/\u03c8 with |y| < 2.4 but missing the lower p T part of the spectrum at midrapidity, while AL-ICE will measured J/\u03c8 in rapidity ranges of |y| < 0.8 and 2.5 < y < 4, at all p T . ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "This measurement should be performed in the four experiments and compared. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "More generally, a detailed study for all observables should be performed regarding the multiplicity.",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Recently, the CMS experiment showed an interesting and unexpected feature of high multiplicity events in proton-proton collisions [15]. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 130,
                    "end": 134,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b15",
                    "text": "[15]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The observed long range correlations are hard to interpret, but already tells us that high multiplicity proton-proton collisions are not trivial.",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
